SIMPLE WEB STACK INFRASTRUCTURE
================================

USER REQUEST FLOW:
User types www.foobar.com in browser
→ DNS resolves www.foobar.com to IP 8.8.8.8
→ Request reaches our single server
→ Nginx handles the request
→ Application server processes it
→ MySQL database provides data
→ Response sent back to user

COMPONENTS:
-----------
1. SERVER: A physical/virtual machine with IP 8.8.8.8 that hosts all components.

2. DOMAIN NAME (foobar.com): Translates human-readable address to IP 8.8.8.8.
   www is a CNAME or A record pointing to 8.8.8.8.

3. DNS RECORD: "www" is an A record pointing to IP 8.8.8.8.

4. WEB SERVER (Nginx): Receives HTTP/HTTPS requests, serves static files,
   forwards dynamic requests to application server.

5. APPLICATION SERVER: Executes business logic, processes dynamic content,
   communicates with database.

6. DATABASE (MySQL): Stores and manages website data.

7. COMMUNICATION PROTOCOL: HTTP/HTTPS over TCP/IP between server and user.

ISSUES WITH THIS INFRASTRUCTURE:
---------------------------------
1. SPOF (Single Point of Failure): If the server goes down, entire website is down.

2. DOWNTIME DURING MAINTENANCE: Deploying new code requires restarting Nginx,
   causing website unavailability.

3. CANNOT SCALE: Single server cannot handle high traffic loads.
   No load balancing or horizontal scaling possible.
